# Odoo Git Commit Guidelines

Follow the official Odoo git commit message format.

## Commit Message Structure

```
[TAG] module_name: short description (< 50 chars ideal)

Long description explaining WHY the change is being done, not WHAT.
WHAT is visible in the diff. Explain technical decisions if any.

References:
{{ ticket_prefix }}-123
Fixes #123
```

## Tags

Use exactly one of these tags as prefix:

| Tag | When to use |
|-----|-------------|
| `[FIX]` | Bug fixes. Mostly stable versions, also valid for recent bugs in dev. |
| `[IMP]` | Improvements. Most dev changes are incremental improvements. |
| `[ADD]` | Adding new modules or major new features. |
| `[REM]` | Removing resources: dead code, views, modules. |
| `[REF]` | Refactoring. Feature heavily rewritten, no functional change. |
| `[MOV]` | Moving files (`git mv`). Don't change content of moved files. |
| `[REV]` | Reverting commits that caused issues. |
| `[REL]` | Release commits: new major/minor stable versions. |
| `[MERGE]` | Merge commits, forward ports. |
| `[CLA]` | Signing contributor license. |
| `[I18N]` | Translation file changes. |
| `[PERF]` | Performance patches. |
| `[CLN]` | Code cleanup. |
| `[LINT]` | Linting passes. |

## Module Name

- Use the **technical** module name (not functional), e.g. `{{ module_prefix }}_project_software`
- If several modules modified: list them or use `various`
- Avoid cross-module changes in one commit when possible

## Header Rules

- **Max ~50 chars** (hard limit ~72).
- Must make a valid sentence after "if applied, this commit will…":
  - Good: `[IMP] {{ module_prefix }}_sale: add discount field to order line`
  - Bad: `[IMP] {{ module_prefix }}_sale: bugfix` or `[IMP] {{ module_prefix }}_sale: improvements`
- Imperative mood: "add", "fix", "remove", "prevent" — not "added", "fixing".
- No single words like "bugfix" / "improvements".
- No ticket numbers in the header — put them in the body.

## Body Rules

- Explain **WHY**, not WHAT (the diff shows WHAT); explain technical decisions.
- End with references (task IDs, PR numbers) on separate lines.
- Separate header from body with a blank line.

## How to Apply

When the user asks to commit (or the pipeline creates commits):

1. Run `git diff --cached --stat` to see what changed
2. Determine the correct tag based on the nature of changes
3. Identify the module name from the changed file paths
4. Write a concise header in imperative mood
5. Write a body explaining WHY if the change is non-trivial
6. Add task references if known from context

## Examples

```
[FIX] {{ module_prefix }}_project_software: prevent stage change by unauthorized users

Only assignees, task assignors, and the project manager can now change
task stages. Previously any project user could move tasks between stages.

{{ ticket_prefix }}-797
```

```
[IMP] {{ module_prefix }}_project_software: add Excel export for gantt chart

New "Export Excel" button in the gantt toolbar downloads an .xlsx file
with color-coded task bars per day, frozen panes, and progress %.
Replaces the previous Mermaid-based export.

{{ ticket_prefix }}-797
Closes #626
```

```
[ADD] {{ module_prefix }}_warehouse: new module for warehouse management

Adds picking wave planning, zone-based storage allocation, and
barcode scanning integration for the warehouse team.

{{ ticket_prefix }}-850

```
